7152 inline SplitQualType SplitQualType::getSingleStepDesugaredType() const {
7153  SplitQualType desugar =
7154  Ty->getLocallyUnqualifiedSingleStepDesugaredType().split();
7155  desugar.Quals.addConsistentQualifiers(Quals);
7156  return desugar;
7157 }

7159 inline const Type *QualType::getTypePtr() const {
7160  return getCommonPtr()->BaseType;
7161 }

7164  return (isNull() ? nullptr : getCommonPtr()->BaseType);

7167 inline bool QualType::isReferenceable() const {
7168  // C++ [defns.referenceable]
7169  // type that is either an object type, a function type that does not have
7170  // cv-qualifiers or a ref-qualifier, or a reference type.
7171  const Type &Self = **this;
7172  if (Self.isObjectType() || Self.isReferenceType())
7173  return true;
7174  if (const auto *F = Self.getAs<FunctionProtoType>())
7175  return F->getMethodQuals().empty() && F->getRefQualifier() == RQ_None;
7176 
7177  return false;
7178 }
7179 
7180 inline SplitQualType QualType::split() const {
7181  if (!hasLocalNonFastQualifiers())
7182  return SplitQualType(getTypePtrUnsafe(),
7183  Qualifiers::fromFastMask(getLocalFastQualifiers()));
7184 
7185  const ExtQuals *eq = getExtQualsUnsafe();
7186  Qualifiers qs = eq->getQualifiers();
7187  qs.addFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
7188  return SplitQualType(eq->getBaseType(), qs);
7189 }
7190 
7191 inline Qualifiers QualType::getLocalQualifiers() const {
7192  Qualifiers Quals;
7193  if (hasLocalNonFastQualifiers())
7194  Quals = getExtQualsUnsafe()->getQualifiers();
7195  Quals.addFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
7196  return Quals;
7197 }
7198 
7199 inline Qualifiers QualType::getQualifiers() const {
7200  Qualifiers quals = getCommonPtr()->CanonicalType.getLocalQualifiers();
7201  quals.addFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
7202  return quals;
7203 }

7205 inline unsigned QualType::getCVRQualifiers() const {
7206  unsigned cvr = getCommonPtr()->CanonicalType.getLocalCVRQualifiers();
7207  cvr |= getLocalCVRQualifiers();
7208  return cvr;
7209 }

7212  QualType canon = getCommonPtr()->CanonicalType;
7213  return canon.withFastQualifiers(getLocalFastQualifiers());
7214 }

7216 inline bool QualType::isCanonical() const {
7217  return getTypePtr()->isCanonicalUnqualified();
7218 }

7220 inline bool QualType::isCanonicalAsParam() const {
7221  if (!isCanonical()) return false;
7222  if (hasLocalQualifiers()) return false;
7223 
7224  const Type *T = getTypePtr();
7225  if (T->isVariablyModifiedType() && T->hasSizedVLAType())
7226  return false;
7227 
7228  return !isa<FunctionType>(T) &&
7229  (!isa<ArrayType>(T) || isa<ArrayParameterType>(T));
7230 }

7312 inline FunctionType::ExtInfo getFunctionExtInfo(const Type &t) {
7313  if (const auto *PT = t.getAs<PointerType>()) {
7314  if (const auto *FT = PT->getPointeeType()->getAs<FunctionType>())
7315  return FT->getExtInfo();
7316  } else if (const auto *FT = t.getAs<FunctionType>())
7317  return FT->getExtInfo();
7318

7326 /// Determine whether this type is more
7327 /// qualified than the Other type. For example, "const volatile int"
7328 /// is more qualified than "const int", "volatile int", and
7329 /// "int". However, it is not more qualified than "const volatile
7330 /// int".
7331 inline bool QualType::isMoreQualifiedThan(QualType other) const {
7332  Qualifiers MyQuals = getQualifiers();
7333  Qualifiers OtherQuals = other.getQualifiers();
7334  return (MyQuals != OtherQuals && MyQuals.compatiblyIncludes(OtherQuals));
7335 }
7336 
7337 /// Determine whether this type is at last
7338 /// as qualified as the Other type. For example, "const volatile
7339 /// int" is at least as qualified as "const int", "volatile int",
7340 /// "int", and "const volatile int".
7341 inline bool QualType::isAtLeastAsQualifiedAs(QualType other) const {
7342  Qualifiers OtherQuals = other.getQualifiers();
7343 
7344  // Ignore __unaligned qualifier if this type is a void.
7345  if (getUnqualifiedType()->isVoidType())
7346  OtherQuals.removeUnaligned();
7347 
7348  return getQualifiers().compatiblyIncludes(OtherQuals);
7349 }
7350 
7351 /// If Type is a reference type (e.g., const
7352 /// int&), returns the type that the reference refers to ("const
7353 /// int"). Otherwise, returns the type itself. This routine is used
7354 /// throughout Sema to implement C++ 5p6:
7355 ///
7356 /// If an expression initially has the type "reference to T" (8.3.2,
7357 /// 8.5.3), the type is adjusted to "T" prior to any further
7358 /// analysis, the expression designates the object or function
7359 /// denoted by the reference, and the expression is an lvalue.
7360 inline QualType QualType::getNonReferenceType() const {
7361  if (const auto *RefType = (*this)->getAs<ReferenceType>())
7362  return RefType->getPointeeType();
7363  else
7364  return *this;
7365 }
7366 
7367 inline bool QualType::isCForbiddenLValueType() const {
7368  return ((getTypePtr()->isVoidType() && !hasQualifiers()) ||
7369  getTypePtr()->isFunctionType());
7370 }

7372 /// Tests whether the type is categorized as a fundamental type.
7373 ///
7374 /// \returns True for types specified in C++0x [basic.fundamental].
7375 inline bool Type::isFundamentalType() const {
7376  return isVoidType() ||
7377  isNullPtrType() ||
7378  // FIXME: It's really annoying that we don't have an
7379  // 'isArithmeticType()' which agrees with the standard definition.
7380  (isArithmeticType() && !isEnumeralType());
7381 }
7382 
7383 /// Tests whether the type is categorized as a compound type.
7384 ///
7385 /// \returns True for types specified in C++0x [basic.compound].
7386 inline bool Type::isCompoundType() const {
7387  // C++0x [basic.compound]p1:
7388  // Compound types can be constructed in the following ways:
7389  // -- arrays of objects of a given type [...];
7390  return isArrayType() ||
7391  // -- functions, which have parameters of given types [...];
7392  isFunctionType() ||
7393  // -- pointers to void or objects or functions [...];
7394  isPointerType() ||
7395  // -- references to objects or functions of a given type. [...]
7396  isReferenceType() ||
7397  // -- classes containing a sequence of objects of various types, [...];
7398  isRecordType() ||
7399  // -- unions, which are classes capable of containing objects of different
7400  // types at different times;
7401  isUnionType() ||
7402  // -- enumerations, which comprise a set of named constant values. [...];
7403  isEnumeralType() ||
7404  // -- pointers to non-static class members, [...].
7405  isMemberPointerType();
7406 }

7436 inline bool Type::isObjectPointerType() const {
7437  // Note: an "object pointer type" is not the same thing as a pointer to an
7438  // object type; rather, it is a pointer to an object type or a pointer to cv
7439  // void.
7440  if (const auto *T = getAs<PointerType>())
7441  return !T->getPointeeType()->isFunctionType();
7442  else
7443  return false;

7760 bool IsEnumDeclComplete(EnumDecl *);

7763 inline bool Type::isIntegerType() const {
7764  if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
7765  return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::Bool &&
7766  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::Int128;
7767  if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType)) {
7768  // Incomplete enum types are not treated as integer types.
7769  // FIXME: In C++, enum types are never integer types.
7770  return IsEnumDeclComplete(ET->getDecl()) &&
7771  !IsEnumDeclScoped(ET->getDecl());
7772  }
7773  return isBitIntType();
7774 }
7775 
7776 inline bool Type::isFixedPointType() const {
7777  if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType)) {
7778  return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::ShortAccum &&
7779  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::SatULongFract;
7780  }
7781  return false;
7782 }

7794  return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::SatShortAccum &&
7795  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::SatULongFract;
7796  }

7804 inline bool Type::isSignedFixedPointType() const {
7805  if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType)) {
7806  return ((BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::ShortAccum &&
7807  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::LongAccum) ||
7808  (BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::ShortFract &&
7809  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::LongFract) ||
7810  (BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::SatShortAccum &&
7811  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::SatLongAccum) ||
7812  (BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::SatShortFract &&
7813  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::SatLongFract));
7814  }
7815  return false;
7816 }
7817 
7818 inline bool Type::isUnsignedFixedPointType() const {
7819  return isFixedPointType() && !isSignedFixedPointType();
7820 }
7821 
7822 inline bool Type::isScalarType() const {
7823  if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
7824  return BT->getKind() > BuiltinType::Void &&
7825  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::NullPtr;
7826  if (const EnumType *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType))
7827  // Enums are scalar types, but only if they are defined. Incomplete enums
7828  // are not treated as scalar types.
7829  return IsEnumDeclComplete(ET->getDecl());
7830  return isa<PointerType>(CanonicalType) ||
7831  isa<BlockPointerType>(CanonicalType) ||
7832  isa<MemberPointerType>(CanonicalType) ||
7833  isa<ComplexType>(CanonicalType) ||
7834  isa<ObjCObjectPointerType>(CanonicalType) ||
7835  isBitIntType();
7836 }
7837 
7838 inline bool Type::isIntegralOrEnumerationType() const {
7839  if (const auto *BT = dyn_cast<BuiltinType>(CanonicalType))
7840  return BT->getKind() >= BuiltinType::Bool &&
7841  BT->getKind() <= BuiltinType::Int128;
7842 
7843  // Check for a complete enum type; incomplete enum types are not properly an
7844  // enumeration type in the sense required here.
7845  if (const auto *ET = dyn_cast<EnumType>(CanonicalType))
7846  return IsEnumDeclComplete(ET->getDecl());
7847 
7848  return isBitIntType();
7849 }

7854  return false;

7933 // Helper class template that is used by Type::getAs to ensure that one does
7934 // not try to look through a qualified type to get to an array type.
7935 template <typename T>
7936 using TypeIsArrayType =
7937  std::integral_constant<bool, std::is_same<T, ArrayType>::value ||
7938  std::is_base_of<ArrayType, T>::value>;
7939 
7940 // Member-template getAs<specific type>'.
7941 template <typename T> const T *Type::getAs() const {
7942  static_assert(!TypeIsArrayType<T>::value,
7943  "ArrayType cannot be used with getAs!");
7944 
7945  // If this is directly a T type, return it.
7946  if (const auto *Ty = dyn_cast<T>(this))
7947  return Ty;
7948 
7949  // If the canonical form of this type isn't the right kind, reject it.
7950  if (!isa<T>(CanonicalType))
7951  return nullptr;
7952 
7953  // If this is a typedef for the type, strip the typedef off without
7954  // losing all typedef information.
7955  return cast<T>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
7956 }
7957 
7958 template <typename T> const T *Type::getAsAdjusted() const {
7959  static_assert(!TypeIsArrayType<T>::value, "ArrayType cannot be used with getAsAdjusted!");
7960 
7961  // If this is directly a T type, return it.
7962  if (const auto *Ty = dyn_cast<T>(this))
7963  return Ty;
7964 
7965  // If the canonical form of this type isn't the right kind, reject it.
7966  if (!isa<T>(CanonicalType))
7967  return nullptr;
7968 
7969  // Strip off type adjustments that do not modify the underlying nature of the
7970  // type.
7971  const Type *Ty = this;
7972  while (Ty) {
7973  if (const auto *A = dyn_cast<AttributedType>(Ty))
7974  Ty = A->getModifiedType().getTypePtr();
7975  else if (const auto *A = dyn_cast<BTFTagAttributedType>(Ty))
7976  Ty = A->getWrappedType().getTypePtr();
7977  else if (const auto *E = dyn_cast<ElaboratedType>(Ty))
7978  Ty = E->desugar().getTypePtr();
7979  else if (const auto *P = dyn_cast<ParenType>(Ty))
7980  Ty = P->desugar().getTypePtr();
7981  else if (const auto *A = dyn_cast<AdjustedType>(Ty))
7982  Ty = A->desugar().getTypePtr();
7983  else if (const auto *M = dyn_cast<MacroQualifiedType>(Ty))
7984  Ty = M->desugar().getTypePtr();
7985  else
7986  break;
7987  }
7988 
7989  // Just because the canonical type is correct does not mean we can use cast<>,
7990  // since we may not have stripped off all the sugar down to the base type.
7991  return dyn_cast<T>(Ty);
7992 }
7993 
7994 inline const ArrayType *Type::getAsArrayTypeUnsafe() const {
7995  // If this is directly an array type, return it.
7996  if (const auto *arr = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(this))
7997  return arr;
7998 
7999  // If the canonical form of this type isn't the right kind, reject it.
8000  if (!isa<ArrayType>(CanonicalType))
8001  return nullptr;
8002 
8003  // If this is a typedef for the type, strip the typedef off without
8004  // losing all typedef information.
8005  return cast<ArrayType>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
8006 }
8007 
8008 template <typename T> const T *Type::castAs() const {
8009  static_assert(!TypeIsArrayType<T>::value,
8010  "ArrayType cannot be used with castAs!");
8011 
8012  if (const auto *ty = dyn_cast<T>(this)) return ty;
8013  assert(isa<T>(CanonicalType));
8014  return cast<T>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
8015 }
8016 
8017 inline const ArrayType *Type::castAsArrayTypeUnsafe() const {
8018  assert(isa<ArrayType>(CanonicalType));
8019  if (const auto *arr = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(this)) return arr;
8020  return cast<ArrayType>(getUnqualifiedDesugaredType());
8021 }
